{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS 1 review — criterion G6 (approach soundness, anti-patterns & alternative-selection): CLEAN, no findings.\n\nAffirmations (criteria this plan satisfies for G6):\n- MECHANISM CORRECTNESS: verified against code. The plan's load-bearing claim that the stable parent plan lives in the SYSTEM PROMPT (not the user message) is correct — `passes.pass1_container` builds the RunRequest with `system_prompt=_resolve_system(PASS_CONTAINER, parent_plan, cfg)` (passes.py:257) while the per-child whole content is in `instructions` (passes.py:258-264); caching is applied anthropic-gated at the shared runner seam on that system block (runner.py:209-222). So S1's \"cache the system prompt, anthropic_cache_instructions\" is mechanically sound and avoids touching the structured-output retry path.\n- The warm-then-fan-out is the correct fix for the real hazard: a naive concurrent fan-out would make every pairing MISS+WRITE the whole-parent cache prefix (~20x input, no read benefit). Warming gate (`parent_tokens >= CACHE_MIN_PREFIX_TOKENS and len(pairings) >= 2`, pass1.py:165) plus a fan-out READ pool is logic-complete. Edge/failure cases are handled explicitly: too-big pairing -> DET failure finding with no LLM call (pass1.py:149-150); systemic LLMUnavailableError on the WARM call aborts the tier (pass1.py:171-182); non-systemic warm failure degrades to direct all-pairings fan-out and the failed pairing re-runs in the pool (no silent drop, pass1.py:183-205); per-pairing failure in the pool drops only that pairing's findings, matching the sequential baseline (pass1.py:222-241). The aggregate finding set equals the sequential baseline (no dup/drop) — no hidden ordering/atomicity assumption.\n- FITNESS-FOR-PURPOSE: attacks the named problem (sequential 2*N_children wall-time + re-sent parent plan), not a proxy — parallelization addresses wall-clock, system-prompt caching addresses re-sent token cost, and S6's semantic eval harness directly guards the fidelity AC.\n- BUDGET-CAP fix is sound and fidelity-preserving: G3/G4 are NEVER shed (sizing.py:198-206, 232-242); the cap bounds only sheddable single-turn/agent/overlay spend, with the container fan-out modeled as a fixed cost floor. This is the cost-model fix, not centrality-inversion.\n- APPROACH SELECTION: reviewer-generated structural alternatives are all addressed/dominated. (a) \"2 parallel whole-plan calls\" — explicitly out-of-scope with a stated reason (trades back per-child fidelity). (b) cache the user message — the plan correctly rejects this (would break the structured-output retry path) and places the stable bytes in the system prompt instead. (c) invert centrality scaling to keep spend under cap — explicitly rejected because it would shed G3/G4 first. Chosen approach is defensibly at-least-as-good on codebase-alignment, blast-radius (one opaque `batch` step; interpreter/YAML untouched), testability (eval-gated S4/S5 + parity harness), simplicity, and robustness.\n- POSITIVE RATIONALE present throughout: the Context, Remediation, and Sequencing-note sections state WHY the shared-runner seam, WHY system-prompt caching, WHY warm-then-fan-out, WHY the cost-model fix, and WHY the de-risk DAG ordering (fidelity-neutral pieces ship ahead of eval-gated S4/S5)."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782578463247409001,"uuid":"fe5b0266-99e4-4a2e-81ff-926ed5dd0e2b"}